et","Presacral space"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eperineum\u003C/strong\u003E represents the region below the pelvic diaphragm. It is a diamond-shaped area bounded by four key landmarks: the pubic symphysis anteriorly, the ischial tuberosities laterally, and the tip of the coccyx posteriorly. This region contains the external genitalia and anal opening.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Efalse pelvis\u003C/strong\u003E represents the expanded superior portion of the pelvis above the pelvic brim. The \u003Cstrong\u003Etrue pelvis\u003C/strong\u003E is the region between the pelvic brim superiorly and the pelvic diaphragm inferiorly. The \u003Cstrong\u003Epelvic inlet\u003C/strong\u003E marks the boundary between the false and true pelvis. The \u003Cstrong\u003Epresacral space\u003C/strong\u003E is located within the true pelvis behind the rectum.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe pelvic diaphragm itself consists of the levator ani muscle complex and the coccygeus muscles, which together create a bowl-shaped muscular floor that supports the pelvic organs and helps maintain continence.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The pelvic diaphragm creates a muscular boundary that divides the pelvic cavity above from the perineal region below.","The perineum is the diamond-shaped anatomical region bounded by the pubic symphysis, ischial tuberosities, and coccyx, housing the external genitalia and anus."],"references":["Arulkumaran, S., Ledger, W., Denny, L., \u0026 Doumouchtsis, S. (Eds.). (2019). Oxford Textbook of Obstetrics and Gynaecology. Oxford University Press","Padubidri, V. G., \u0026 Daftary, S. N. (Eds.). (2014). Shaw\u0027s Textbook of Gynecology E-book. Elsevier health sciences","Raizada V, Mittal RK. Pelvic floor anatomy and applied physiology. Gastroenterol Clin North Am. 2008 Sep;37(3):493-509, vii. doi: 10.1016/j.gtc.2008.06.003. PMID: 18793993; PMCID: PMC2617789"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98539"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15758"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98539","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/98539"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-29T19:41:14+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-29T19:41:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8449"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116546"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4931","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4931"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Musculoskeletal","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-31T09:50:31+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"13"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemC